Phase 0: One-Time Setup (Do This First)
Before deploying to any environment, complete these one-time setup steps on your forked repository.
 
0.1 — Rename Your Forked Repository
Your repo name must follow the naming convention: python-etl-{business-context-or-purpose}
• Go to: Helios Developer Portal → GitHub Automation → Rename Your Repo
• Enter App Code: cdn0 (or your app code)
• Search for your forked repo: e.g., cdn0-python-etl-ga-template
• Enter new repo name: e.g., python-etl-credit-card-alerts
⚠️ Note: Name must be all lowercase, hyphen-separated, prefixed with python-etl-
 
0.2 — Modify setup.py
Located at the root of your repo.
File / Location
Parameter / Line
What to Change
setup.py
Line 14 — name field
Change to: cdn0-python-etl-{your-repo-name} Example: 'cdn0-python-etl-credit-card-alerts'
setup.py
Line 16 — description
Optional: Enter a meaningful description of your pipeline
 
0.3 — Modify src/__init__.py
This file controls the version number. Every time you push to master you MUST update this.
File / Location
Parameter / Line
What to Change
src/__init__.py
Line 1 — __version__
Set initial version: __version__ = "1.0.0" Follow semantic versioning (MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH)
⚠️ Note: You MUST increment this version every time you merge to master, otherwise Helios will not redeploy.
 
0.4 — Add Your Python Script to src/data_pipeline/
• Copy your converted Python ETL script into: src/data_pipeline/
• Rename it meaningfully: e.g., credit_card_alerts_processing.py
• Keep the template file: pipeline_template_job_one.py as reference
• Your ETL logic should contain an importable function that main.py will call
 
0.5 — Update requirements.txt
Add any additional Python packages your script needs.
File / Location
Parameter / Line
What to Change
requirements.txt
Append new lines
Add packages beyond defaults (PyYAML, pydeequ, pytest, pytest-cov, coverage) Example: pandas, boto3, pyarrow
 
0.6 — Configure Your YAML File in config/
Create a YAML config file for each environment. This is the only place to hardcode source/destination paths.
• Create: config/{your-repo-name}-dev.yaml
• Create: config/{your-repo-name}-staging.yaml
• Create: config/{your-repo-name}-prod.yaml
○ Each file should contain: job_name, input/output Hadoop/S3 paths, and any other key-value parameters
⚠️ Note: Your Python code must reference this yaml file for all paths. Do NOT hardcode paths in .py files.
 
0.7 — Update main.py
Located at src/main.py. This is the entry point called by Airflow via spark_submit.sh.
